                      <span>0</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2001-12-17</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>Leonard Koppett's book does not get a 5 star rating by me only because it is hard to rate a textbook as a 5. Still, this is a great book. It is along the lines of an SABR release, though the statistics are of a different type. I liked this book, but it will appeal only to those who want a deeper understanding of how the game has mirrored society and how the issues of today are not unlike those of the past. This is a history project, but a very good one. Read this with some of the histories by Harold Seymour and the game will appear much different come the spring. I would also recommend BASEBALL by Ken Burns and Geoffrey Ward.<BR>I admire Koppett greatly for attempting such a project as this <BR>CONCISE HISTORY OF MAJOR LEAGUE BASEBALL.</span>
                  
              
